Product Version     25.10    Cadence Design Systems, Inc.
editMove(25.10)                                                editMove(25.10)

Name
       editMove - Moves selected wires, boundary pins, or vias

Syntax
       editMove

       [-help]

       {[[-direction  {x  y  diag45 diag135} -distance <float>] | [-dx <float>
       -dy <float>] | -to {x y}] }

       Moves selected wires, boundary pins, or vias.

Moving Wires
       editMove moves selected wires in the orthogonal  direction.  When  used
       with  the -direction and -distance or -dx and -dy combination, editMove
       maintains connectivity by stretching connected wires in the  orthogonal
       direction. This command also supports 45 and 135-degree wire edits.

       Use  the setEditMode -connect_with_specified_layer parameter to control
       whether layer preference settings are honored when wires are moved. The
       default value of this parameter is 0. If you set this parameter  to  1,
       editMove  honors  the setEditMode -layer_horizontal and -layer_vertical
       settings while jogging metal layers. For instance, if you cut a  verti-
       cal  wire on M4 by using editCutWire such that the wire is divided into
       three wire segments and then move the wire segment in the middle in the
       horizontal direction, the tool  automatically  creates  new  connecting
       wires  on  the layer defined by setEditMode -layer_horizontal and drops
       vias correctly. This means you no longer need to perform the additional
       step for layer change (editChangeLayer or Shift+L) while  moving  wires
       to  create  a jog. This feature is applicable for both regular and spe-
       cial wires.

       To get the current value of the  -connect_with_specified_layer  parame-
       ter, you can use the corresponding getEditMode parameter.

       Note:    You    can    use    the    setEditMode   -snap_to_track   and
       -snap_to_track_regular parameters to specify whether  or  not  to  snap
       wires  to the track. To get the current values of these parameters, use
       the corresponding getEditMode options.

Moving Physical Pins
       editMove moves selected physical pins along with connected wires.

       Keep the following considerations in mind while trying to move a physi-
       cal pin with editMove:

              * editMove can be used to move only the physical pins on the de-
                sign boundary. Pins inside the design  cannot  be  moved  with
                this command.

              * A pin can be moved only along a boundary.

              * It cannot be moved between design boundaries.

              * Pins  on the top or bottom boundary can be moved only horizon-
                tally.

              * Pins on the left or right boundary can be  moved  only  verti-
                cally.

       Note:  You can use the setEditMode-snap_to_track_pin parameter to spec-
       ify whether or not to snap moved pins to the track. This  parameter  is
       set to true (1) by default. To get the current value of this parameter,
       use the corresponding getEditMode option.

Parameters
       -help  Prints  the  usage of the command. For a detailed description of
              the command, use the man command:

              man editMove

       -direction {x y diag45 diag135}
              Specifies the direction of movement. Use one  of  the  following
              options:

              * diag45  -  Moves selected wires the specified <-distance> in a
                45-degree direction.This option  cannot  be  used  for  moving
                physical pins.

              * diag135  - Moves selected wires the specified <-distance> in a
                135-degree direction. This option cannot be  used  for  moving
                physical pins.

              * x - Moves selected vertical wires or pins to the right (if you
                specify  a  positive  value  for  <-distance>) or left (if you
                specify a negative value for <-distance>).

              * y - Moves selected horizontal wires or pins up (if you specify
                a positive value for <-distance>) or down (if  you  specify  a
                negative value for <-distance>).

       -distance <float>
              Specifies the distance to move the wire or pin in microns.

       -dx <float>
              Specifies  the  distance  in  microns by which the selected wire
              should be moved in the x direction. You  must  specify  the  -dy
              value  along  with it. For example, if you want to move the wire
              in the x direction by 0.2 microns, specify  the  following  com-
              mand:

              editMove -dx 0.2 -dy 0

       -dy <float>
              Specifies  the  distance  in  microns by which the selected wire
              should be moved in the y direction. You  must  specify  the  -dx
              value  along  with it. For example, if you want to move the wire
              in the y direction by 0.2 microns, specify  the  following  com-
              mand:

              editMove -dx 0 -dy 0.2

       -to {x y}
              Specifies  the  coordinates of the new location to which the se-
              lected wire or via is to be moved. If you are moving a via,  the
              x and y values specify the new coordinates of the via origin. In
              the  case  of a wire, the x and y values specify the new coordi-
              nates of the lower left corner of the wire. See Examples.

              When you move the selected wire or via with editMove  -to,  con-
              nected wires are not moved.

Examples
              * The  following  command  moves the selected wire such that its
                lower-left corner lies on the coordinates  {20,30}  after  the
                move:

                editMove -to {20 30}

              *

                The  following  command  moves  the selected via such that its
                origin lies on the coordinates {20, 30} after the move:

                editMove -to {20 30}

